04806nam a22008655i 9780520925205DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20022002cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209252057 a10.1525/97805209252052doi  a(DE-B1597)521001  a(OCoLC)326626702  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aQL 7aSCI0080002bisacsh1 aGrismer, L. Lee, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmphibians and Reptiles of Baja California, Including Its Pacific Islands and the Islands in the Sea of Cortés /cL. Lee Grismer. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (413 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aOrganisms and Environments ;v40 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Baja California peninsula is home to many forms of life found nowhere else on earth. This, combined with the peninsula's rugged and inaccessible terrain, has made the area one of the last true biological frontiers of North America. L. Lee Grismer is not only the foremost authority on the amphibians and reptiles of Baja California, but also an outstanding photographer. He has produced the most comprehensive work on the herpetofauna of the peninsula and its islands ever published. With its stunning color images, detailed accounts of many little-known species, and descriptions of the region's diverse environment, this is the definitive guide to the amphibians and reptiles of a fascinating and remote region.The culmination of Grismer's quarter century of fieldwork on the Baja peninsula and his exploration of more than one hundred of its islands in the Pacific Ocean and the Sea of Cortés, this book gives information on the identification, distribution, natural history, and taxonomy of each species of amphibian and reptile found there. Preliminary accounts of the life history of many of the salamanders, frogs, toads, turtles, lizards, and snakes are reported here for the first time, and several species that were almost unknown to science are illustrated in full color. The book also contains new data on species distribution and on the effect of the isolated landscape of the peninsula and its islands on the evolutionary process. Much of the information gathered here is presented in biogeographical overviews that consider the extremely varied environments of Baja California in both a contemporary and a historical framework. An original and important contribution to science, this book will generate further research for years to come as it becomes a benchmark reference for both professionals and amateurs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Biology.2bisacsh  aamphibians.  abaja california.  abiogeography.  abiological frontiers.  abiology.  acalifornia.  aenvironment.  aforms of life.  afrogs.  ageckos.  aherpetofauna.  ahistorical biogeography.  aiguanas.  aislands.  alizards.  anorth america.  apeninsula.  aphotography.  areptiles.  asalamanders.  asnakes.  ataxonomy.  aterrain.  atoads.  atortoises.  atreefrogs.  aturtles.  aunited states of america.  awhiptails.  aworm lizards.1 aGreene, Harry W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092520540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520925205423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520925205/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles